Anonymous Fri 07 Jun 2024 01:41:11 No.66389190 Report
Quoted By: >>66389234
>>66388438
>First
Good for character studies and smaller self contained narratives, really allows the reader to get into the head of the protagonist for obvious reasons. Can sometimes be difficult to write in since all the information that the reader's given must also be known/discovered by the protagonist.

>Second
Good for exactly one type of story and that's a greentext, preferably on the shorter side, with a self insert protag and made with the intention of being posted in the thread. The format starts getting clunkier the longer the story goes on.

>Third
A very adaptable type of perspective, ideal if you're writing something with lots of lore. Shifting between third person limited and third person omniscient gives you a very fine level of control over information given to the reader, third person limited can also allow you to subtly shift between character perspectives in a chapter without being as obvious as in first person. If you aren't sure what perspective to use for a story it's hard to fuck up third person.

The reader will visualize the action and develop a sense of presence that only the best narration can hope to match. Remember that that's what narration does, it supplies a framework for mental imagery when there is no visual action or other context for Reader to work with.

>you think it's too spaced out?
He is spacing out, but staring out into a room and staring at a chick are different kinds of staring. One is disconnected, the other is intimate (and sometimes sexual assault). That makes "again" have another way to land awkwardly. But mostly I think the problem is that you're Telling he's some degree of drunk, but it's never really portrayed. It read like a grocery list: Go to bar, get drink, consume, pay, leave, [Intoxication stats icon has appeared]. It went too fast to portray this and leaves me in the "well is he fucked up or not?" And the portrayal is tricky because it's easy to go melodramatic by putting a lampshade on his head and having him stagger around on one side and this being technical but not practical impairment which is apparently what you went with because he drove home and didn't crash but if that's the case why imply in the text that he wasn't really fit to roll.
